               <p>ROBERT POOLE. I am a <rs id="t18300415-241-viclabel1334" type="occupation">glazier</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-241-victim2104 t18300415-241-viclabel1334"></join>. I was in the neighbourhood of <placeName id="t18300415-241-crimeloc1335">Brick-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-241-crimeloc1335" type="placeName" value="Brick-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-241-crimeloc1335" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-241-off1332 t18300415-241-crimeloc1335"></join> between ten and eleven o'clock at night, on the 14th of February - I was sober; I met Tye and another woman, not in custody - they asked me for a glass of gin, as it was very cold; I said I would, but I did not know where to go - one of them, I believe<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183004150115"></xptr>Tye, said, "Come in here, Sir;" they then led me into a house, and I went up five or six steps - I saw a very large fire in a grate, and I thought it was all right, but on turning round I saw a bed; I said, "This is not the place I wanted to come to" - one of them said, "Nobody will hurt you, but you will stand a drop of something to drink;" I said "I shall have no objection" - I took out sixpence, which I either put on the table or into Tye's hand; at that moment Clarkson came in, and Tye said, "The young man is going to give us something to drink;" she took the sixpence and a bottle - I said "I am off;" the other said, "You will not go" - I stopped till the gin came, and did just taste it; Clarkson then came and put her arms round me, and said, "You will not be off, stop and sleep with my neice Eliza;" I said "It is late, and I must go to my brother" - she said, "What time is it?" I pulled out my watch - Clarkson took it and ran off; I turned round, and one of the girls knocked out the candle - I said, "I see what sort of a house I am in, I will take the whole lot of you if I can" - I went into the street, and paced in front of the door till the officer came, and we went in.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-241-person2105">
                  WILLIAM 
                  DYKE
               <interp inst="t18300415-241-person2105" type="surname" value="DYKE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-241-person2105" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-241-person2105" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I heard an alarm and went up - the prosecutor said he had been robbed, and would not leave the house till he got his watch; I went in - Clarkson was not to be found, but the landlord said he would send his daughter to a house where she could most likely be found; I went backwards - Clarkson was going up stairs, and I took her; she denied having it at all - I was going to search her; she produced it from her shawl, with this diamond.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-241-person2106">
                  ROBERT 
                  POOLE
               <interp inst="t18300415-241-person2106" type="surname" value="POOLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-241-person2106" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-241-person2106" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . This watch is mine, and this diamond, which I suppose she got out of my pocket - the other two girls did not touch me.</p>
               <p>Clarkson's Defence. He gave me the watch to look what time it was - this woman knew nothing of it; I was sitting in a chair between them - the diamond laid on the table.</p>
               <p>CLARKSON - <rs id="t18300415-241-verdict1336" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-241-verdict1336" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 39.</p>

